sentence-detokenized: CRICKET - LEICESTERSHIRE TAKE THE LEAD AFTER BACK-TO-BACK WINS.
West Indies player Phil Simmons scored four for 38 on Friday as Leicestershire beat Somerset by an innings and 39 runs in two days to take the county championship lead.

However, their stay at the top of the table could be short-lived as title rivals Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey moved closer to victory, while Kent made up for lost time in their rain-affected match with Nottinghamshire.

After dismissing Somerset for 83 on the opening morning at Grace Road, Leicestershire extended their first innings lead to 94 before being bowled out for 296, with England's Andy Caddick, who was dismissed, taking three for 83.
Leading by 213, Somerset got off to a solid start in their second half before Simmons stepped in to dismiss them for 174.
Essex, however, look certain to reclaim their top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Such gave them a firm grip on the Yorkshire match at Headingley.
Hussain, considered surplus to England's one-day requirements, hit 158, his first championship century of the season, as Essex reached 372 and took a first innings lead of 82.
By the close Yorkshire had turned this into a 37-run lead, but off-spinner Such dashed their hopes, taking four for 24 in 48 balls and leaving them hanging on for 119 for five and praying for rain.
At The Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, another man left by England, continued to silence his critics after following up his four for 45 on Thursday with 80 on Friday against Warwickshire.
He was well supported by England hopeful Mark Butcher, who made 70 as Surrey closed on 429 for seven, a lead of 234.
Derbyshire continued their hunt for their first championship title since 1936, reducing Worcestershire to 133 for five in the second innings, still 100 runs away from avoiding defeat.
Australian Tom Moody took six for 82, but Chris Adams, 123, and Tim O'Gorman, 109, took Derbyshire to 471 and a first innings lead of 233.
After the frustration of seeing their opening day match severely affected by the weather, Kent stepped up to knock Nottinghamshire out for 214.
They were backed by a brave 84 from Paul Johnson, but former Englishman Martin McCague took four for 55.
By the stumps Kent was 108 for three.

FOOTBALL - SHEARER NAMED CAPTAIN OF ENGLAND.
The world's most expensive footballer, Alan Shearer, was named England's new captain on Friday.
The 26-year-old, who joined Newcastle for £15 million ($23.4 million), takes over from Tony Adams, who led the team during June's European Championship, and former captain David Platt.
Adams and Platt are both injured and will miss England's opening World Cup qualifier against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer takes over as captain on a trial basis, but new coach Glenn Hoddle said he sees no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton captain should not take the job.
"I'm sure there won't be a problem, I'm sure Alan is the right man for the job," Hoddle said.
"There were three or four people who could have done it, but when I talked to Alan, he was ready and really wanted to do it.
"In four days it's very hard to come to a 100% conclusion about something like this....
but he knows how to behave, his teammates respect him and he knows where the team stands, even if he plays up front. "
Shearer's Euro 96 strike partner Teddy Sheringham withdrew from the squad on Friday due to injury.
He will probably be replaced by Les Ferdinand, Shearer's Newcastle teammate.

FOOTBALL - ROTOFAN BLOCKED AFTER VOLGOGRAD VIOLENCE.

Rotor Volgograd must play their next home game behind closed doors after fans threw bottles and stones at Dinamo Moscow players during Saturday's 1-0 defeat, which ended Rotor's brief stint as league leaders.
The head of the Russian league's disciplinary committee, Anatoly Gorokhovsky, said on Friday that Rotor will play Lada Togliatti on September 3 to empty stands.
The club, which eliminated Manchester United from last year's UEFA Cup, was fined $1,000.
Despite the defeat, Rotor is well placed with 11 games remaining in the championship.
Three points behind Alania and two points behind Dinamo Moscow, the Volgograd side are one game ahead of the leaders and two ahead of the Moscow club.
BOXING - PANAMANIAN ROBERTO DURAN FIGHTS THE SANDS OF TIME.
Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Hands of Stone" Duran steps into the ring on Saturday in a new attempt to sustain his long, age-defying career.
Duran, 45, faces little-known Mexican Ariel Cruz, 30, in a non-title super middleweight bout in Panama City.
The fight, Duran's first on home turf in 10 years, is billed here as the "Return of the Legend," and Duran still talks like he's in his prime.
This match is to prepare me.
I'm not retiring," Duran told Reuters.

But those close to the boxer recognise that the man who has won championships in four different weight classes - lightweight, welterweight, junior middleweight and middleweight - is nearing the end of his career.
"Every time he fights, he's on the final frontier of his career.
If he loses on Saturday, it could devalue his position as one of the world's great boxers," said Panamanian Boxing Association president Ramon Manzanares.
Duran, whose 97-12 record spans three decades, hopes a win in the 10-round bout will earn him a rematch against Hector "Macho" Camacho of Puerto Rico.
Camacho took a controversial points decision against the Panamanian in Atlantic City in June in a title fight.

TENNIS - TARANGO, O'BRIEN SPRING TWO SURPRISES UNDER THE SPOTLIGHT.
Andre Agassi escaped disaster on Thursday, but Wimbledon finalist MaliVai Washington and Marcelo Rios were not so lucky in an evening of surprises at the US Open.
Washington, the 11th seed, failed to repeat his miraculous Wimbledon comeback as he lost to red wildcard Alex O'Brien 6-3 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 in a two-hour, 51-minute battle on the Stadium court.
Next door in the stands, Rios, seeded No. 10, lost to another player with a Wimbledon connection - bad boy Jeff Tarango.
The temperamental left-hander defeated the Chilean 6-4 4-6 4-6 7-6 6-2.

The day's program went off without a hitch, although Agassi, the former sixth-ranked champion, had to battle back from a dangerous 3-6 0-4 deficit to win 18 of his last 19 games against India's Leander Paes.
But the night belonged to the newcomers.
Washington, who came back from a 1-5 deficit to trail by two sets in the third set against Todd Martin in the Wimbledon semifinals, seemed poised for another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, winner two weeks ago in New Haven for his first pro title, served for the match at 5-4 in the third set before Washington stormed back.
"I kept telling myself, 'keep giving yourself your best chance to win, keep fighting, maybe something will happen,'" said the 26-year-old O'Brien, ranked 65th.
"I kept my cool and was proud of myself for that - usually I would have folded up the tent and gone home."
O'Brien, a former U.S. college national champion, managed 17 aces to finally beat Washington, which never gave up.
The fifth set remained on serve until the sixth game, when Washington, after saving a break point with a forehand winner down the line, sent a backhand into the net to give O'Brien a 4-2 lead.
The Texan hit two aces to hold serve at 5-2 and then converted his eighth match point for the win when Washington found the net with another backhand at 40-0.
"You keep fighting and trying to get him to play a little bit.
I think he was a little tense at times," Washington said. "
But I think it served well enough when it had to. "

Tarango, whose tantrum at Wimbledon two years ago earned him a $28,000 fine and suspension from this year's tournament at the All-England Club, argued with fans during the two hours and 24 minutes of lively tango with Rios in the stands.
An enthusiastic audience supported the Chilean entertainer and booed the skinny American, who enjoyed all the attention.
"I'm an emotional player," said Tarango, ranked 104th. "
I think I played very well tonight, I was very focused. "
The match went to a tie-break in the third set, which the American won 7-5, much to the despair of the spectators.
"I love the public even if they boo me every day.
It gets me fired up, makes me play my best tennis," Tarango said.
"I played some of my best tennis in college, when fraternities were throwing beer on me.
If tennis was like this every day, I think everyone would have a lot more fun. "
"He's always complaining too much," Rios said. "
But I think that's not it.
I think we played very badly.
It was hard to play at night.
The balls were going very fast.
I've lost too many points that I never lose.
"I don't see the ball the way I see it during the day.
I play an American, so that's why I play at night.
I didn't feel good on the field. "
At the end of the game, Tarango blew sarcastic kisses to the crowd, then waved his body in front of a section of Rios supporters in salute.
"I support their enthusiasm," Tarango said of the fans. "
At the same time, they are blatantly cheering against me.
After I won, I thought I'd give them a bit of a rant. "
Randall Cunningham, the all-time leading rusher in the National Football League at quarterback and one of the most athletic players to ever line up under center, retired Thursday.
Cunningham played his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
A three-time Pro Bowl selection, Cunningham rushed for 4,482 yards in 677 carries.
"I would like to thank the Eagles organization and the wonderful fans in Philadelphia for supporting me throughout my career," Cunningham said.
"While I am sad to leave, I look forward to spending more time with my family and attending to other interests that have been on the back burner for some time."
"Randall was one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history," said Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie. "
During his 11 years in Philadelphia, Randall was the cornerstone of the Eagles franchise and brought many great moments to fans in Philadelphia and across the NFL."
A second-round pick in 1985, Cunningham completed 1,874 of 3,362 passes (55.7%) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham has already signed a broadcasting contract.
